<h2>Problem</h2>
<p>
The digital patient engagement consent form sat at the tail end of a lengthy digital registration flow. The point where patient fatigue is highest. It was written in dense legal language, buried under multiple scrolls, and visually indistinguishable from the clinical questions that preceded it. Patients were checking box without reading the terms, and the downstream effect was complaints about ads that felt intrusive and unexplained.
</p>

</p>
The company wanted to address this — but the brief came with a hard requirement: Any change that risked lowering opt-in rates was off the table, because each opt-in translated directly to advertising revenue.
</p>

<h2>Process</h2>
<p>
I ran usability research using UserZoom to identify language that patients found confusing or misleading. Participants flagged specific words and phrases that obscured meaning. When I brought those findings to the broader group — which included Legal, Product, the Chief Operating Officer, and the Chief Privacy Officer — the research was dismissed. The concern wasn't the findings themselves, but the platform: because participants were compensated, some felt their responses lacked credibility.
</p>

<p>
That was a turning point. Without the research as a lever, I was left advocating on principle in a room where most people outranked me, and where the primary measure of success was opt-in rate stability.
</p>

<p>
The team also wanted to A/B test nearly every change in isolation, including capitalization and punctuation. I pushed back on this. At that level of granularity, testing doesn't produce insight, it produces delay. But I understood the impulse: the team was trying to manufacture a perfect iteration, one where they could trace exactly which change had caused any movement in rates. The caution wasn't irrational. It just meant the process moved slowly and the scope of what we could change kept narrowing.
</p>

{% decisionbox %}We also proposed moving the consent form into a visually distinct section to signal clearly that this was no longer part of the clinical registration. It was rejected — the concern was that making the distinction too obvious would lower opt-in rates.{% enddecisionbox %}

<h2>Solution</h2>
<p>
What shipped was a condensed form (fewer scrolls to reach the checkbox) and language that was marginally clearer than the original. Opt-in rates remained stable. From the company's perspective, the project was a success.
</p>

<p>
From the patient's perspective, I'm less sure. The changes reduced some friction but didn't address the root problem: patients were still being asked to make a consequential decision at the most fatigued point in a long form, in language designed to protect the business rather than inform the user.
</p>

<h2>Reflection</h2>
<p>
The project brief had a ceiling built into it. The changes most likely to help patients understand what they were agreeing to were rejected because they might reduce opt-ins. The room was never really debating how to fix the problem, just how much of it we could afford to address.
</p>

<p>
What I didn't do was reframe the stakes. The social media complaints were already a reputational risk, and another cycle of them would have been a revenue risk too. That's the argument that would have landed with the COO. Instead I argued on design grounds to a room measuring success in conversion rates, and I kept losing the same argument for the same reason.
</p>

<p>
I'd also go back and build alliances earlier. Lone advocacy in a room that senior rarely moves anything. One person from Legal worried about liability, or a product lead with patient trust on their roadmap, would have shifted the dynamic. The lesson wasn't that I needed to be louder. It was that I needed to not be the only one speaking.
</p>